  "timeframe": "1m",
  "market_context": "After higher-time-frame analysis showed bearish bias from a daily fair value gap and hourly CISD, price on 10/11/2023 built a range on the 1-minute chart and failed to displace higher, setting up for a bearish continuation toward equal lows and standard deviation projections.",
  "key_observation": "Price created a range, manipulated higher but failed to displace, then closed below the last up-close candle producing a change in state of delivery. This sequence — manipulation followed by CISD — defined the bearish entry condition.",
  "analysis_steps": [
    "Step 1: Identify the established range on the 1-minute chart and observe price failing to displace out of it (manipulation phase).",
    "Step 2: Wait for a change in state of delivery — price closing below the last up-close candle within the range.",
    "Step 3: Take the first entry at the CISD or on the retest of the resulting order block, with stop placed above the manipulation high that swept liquidity.",
    "Step 4: Project targets using standard deviations (-2 to -2.5) anchored to the manipulation leg, plus the visible low/equal lows on the chart.",
    "Step 5: If the first entry is missed, look for additional order blocks formed as price continues to close below subsequent up-close candles, restricted to the premium of the dealing range.",
    "Step 6: Monitor delivery — price broke the initial low and reached into the -2 to -2.5 projection as well as the hourly target (old highs/equal lows)."
  ],
  "outcome": "Trade reached its targets — price delivered down to the -2 to -2.5 standard deviation, the -4 level, and ultimately the hourly target.",
  "lessons": "A clean bearish entry model combines three elements: manipulation of a range, a change in state of delivery, and an order block/FVG to deliver price into projected targets. Stops sit on the manipulation high; targets are standard deviation projections paired with visible liquidity.",
